rarchy by allowing some people to move freely while placing limits on the mobility of others. Highlighting the ways people of color have negotiated their place within these systems, Carpio reveals a compelling and perceptive analysis of spatial mobility through physical movement and residence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMigration, InternalzCaliforniazInland Empire. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  a19th century.  a20th century.  aamerican west.  abicycle ordinances.  aeastern suburbs.  ahistorical societies.  aidentity.  aimmigration policy.  aincarceration.  aindian boarding schools.  ainland empire.  alabor.  alocal authorities.  alos angels.  amajor crossroads.  amobility.  apermission to move freely.  apolicies.  aprohibitions on movement.  arace.  aracial formation.  aracial hierarchy.  aresidence.  aroute 66 heritage.  aspatial mobility.  atraffic checkpoints.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520970823zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520970823423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520970823.jpg  a978-3-11-061017-8